<<<explanation>>>: You can measure the time it takes to read from the InputStream and then divide the total bytes read by the time taken to get the bandwidth. Note that this will give you the bandwidth in bytes per second, not bits per second. If you want bits per second, you would need to convert bytes to bits (multiply by 8).


A: You can use the following code to measure the bandwidth used in transferring files with Java sockets:

```java
long startTime = System.nanoTime();
long totalBytesRead = 0;
byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
int bytesRead;
while ((bytesRead = is.read(buffer)) != -1) {
    totalBytesRead += bytesRead;
}
long endTime = System.nanoTime();
long timeTaken = endTime - startTime;
double megabytesPerSecond = totalBytesRead / (timeTaken / 1e9);
```

This code measures the time it takes to read from the InputStream and then divides the total bytes read by the time taken to get the bandwidth. Note that this will give you the bandwidth in bytes per second, not bits per second. If you want bits per second, you would need to convert bytes to bits (multiply by 8).

Also, you can use the following code to read the first 3 bytes and figure out your length:

```java
final byte[] lengthBuffer = new byte[3];
try{
    int b = is.read(lengthBuffer);
    // make sure b was 3 and do your length calculation
    final byte buffer = new byte[length];
    b = is.read(buffer);
    // check b and then you have your bytes
}catch (IOException e){
    System.out.println("Something went wrong.");
}
```

This code reads the first 3 bytes into a buffer and then calculates the length of the data to be read. It also handles any IOException that might occur during the reading process.

I hope this helps you to improve the performance of your code.
